english:
  title: Inscription on the Bamboo-Loving Pavilion with Preface
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A certain Li, a gentleman of Longxi, is a man of noble character. By nature he loves bamboo, and has cultivated a thousand stalks within his home. Thus he built himself a pavilion. When the Esteemed Minister Yeon of the Eastern Pavilion was demoted southward, he would climb to this tower on any given day to dispel the melancholy held within his breast. Recognizing this as the master's truest passion, I bestowed upon the pavilion the name "Bamboo-Loving," and inscribed three grand characters that the master might affix upon his beam—a testament to all who behold it of what he holds dear.

    See how guest and host have found accord in spirit, and how name and substance align in perfect harmony. Surely this warrants inscription.

    The inscription reads:

    The bamboo's grace, a man fulfills through living—
    the tower stands as witness.
    The bamboo's steadfast roots reflect the master's will—
    this name I give with certainty.
    When bamboo serves as measure of the human soul,
    it touches the sublime.
    Therefore I write this inscription.
  footnotes:
    - Longxi (隴西) is a historical region, here used as a place designation indicating the Li family's origin or affiliation.
    - The "Eastern Pavilion" (東亭) and Minister Yeon refer to an esteemed official who found solace in this bamboo pavilion during his period of demotion.
    - The inscription employs a classical form of memorial writing, where the bamboo serves as both literal subject and metaphorical embodiment of human virtue and constancy.
